"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756395","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Government is alive to the concerns around the clustering of betting shops. Since 2015, planning permission has been required for any new betting shops on the high street. In addition, the Gambling Act 2005 requires local authorities to set out in a statement of policy the principles by which they manage the gambling environment in the local area. The statement can be used to set out reasons for why it would be inconsistent with licensing objectives to grant additional licences in a given location e.g. safeguarding children or the vulnerable. The Gambling Commission advise that the use of the licensing statement of policy varies from one Local Authority to another, however where used effectively and regularly updated, they can provide an effective tool for appropriately rejecting new licenses or imposing conditions to improve safeguarding and avoid attempts at clustering.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","8115","2017-09-07T14:07:17.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756395/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756395/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756395/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Betting Shops","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, if she will introduce measures to prevent clustering of betting shops and reform planning guidance on the placement of betting shops.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756396","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Gambling Commission's Gaming Machine Technical Standards states that the game cycle for a B2 gaming machines (also known as Fixed Odds Betting Terminals) must last at least 20 seconds to complete. The Gambling Commission is responsible for ensuring that operators adhere to these requirements. The review of gaming machines and social responsibility measures that I announced in October 2016 includes a close look at the regulation of Fixed Odds Betting Terminals (FOBTs). We are hoping to publish findings in October.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-09-07T14:43:23.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756396/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756396/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756396/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Gaming Machines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, if she will introduce legislation to increase the delay between spins of Fixed Odds Betting Terminals.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7900"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756397","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-07","<p>While addiction is in the main the remit of the Department of Health, I can inform you that the majority of treatment to those experiencing gambling related harm is delivered by GamCare or via the National Problem Gambling Clinic. A range of support is available through these organisations.</p><p> </p><p>A range of services available to problem gamblers can be found on the NHS Choices website, including links to the Money Advice Service at:</p><p>www.nhs.uk/Livewell/addiction/Pages/gamblingaddiction.aspx</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-09-07T14:16:19.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756397/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756397/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756397/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Gambling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what Government assistance is provided to people made financially destitute by gambling addiction.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7901"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756398","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>Since its inception in September 2015, the GCS Knowledge &amp; Capability Unit has made 47 trips to Tunisia on official business. The average cost per trip has been £1,947.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-09-11T14:15:14.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756398/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756398/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756398/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Communication Service: Tunisia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many trips staff from the Government Communication Service have made to Tunisia since the inception of that body; and what the costs were of each such trip.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756399","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>Since its inception in September 2015, the GCS Knowledge &amp; Capability Unit has made 11 trips to Jordan on official business. The average cost per trip has been £2,259.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-09-11T14:13:45.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756399/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756399/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756399/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Communication Service: Jordan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many trips staff from the Government Communication Service have made to Jordan since the inception of that body; and what the costs were of each such trip.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756400","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government Communication Service (GCS) is the professional body for people working in communication roles across Government. Records containing the information requested in these Questions are not held centrally and replies would incur disproportionate costs.</p><p> </p><p>The GCS aims to deliver world-class public service communications that support Government priorities, enable the efficient and effective operation of public services and improve people’s lives.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","8384","2017-09-12T13:17:03.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756400/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756400/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756400/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Communication Service: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many secondments have been organised form (a) the Government Communication Service (GCS) to outside of government and (b) outside of Government to the GCS since the inception of that body.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756401","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>Since its inception in September 2015, the GCS Knowledge &amp; Capability Unit has not seconded any staff members to foreign Governments and as such, no fees have been charged.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-09-11T11:18:36.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756401/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756401/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756401/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Communication Service: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether a fee is charged by the Government for staff seconded to foreign Governments from the Government Communication Service.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756402","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-18","<p>The UK’s relationship with the EU's agencies upon exit will be evaluated in light of<br>delivering the twelve objectives outlined by the Prime Minister to achieve a deep and<br>special partnership between the UK and the EU. The UK’s future relationship with the EU's<br>decentralised bodies after leaving the EU is a matter for the negotiations.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-18T14:28:18.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756402/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756402/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756402/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Cabinet Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of the number of new arms-length bodies his Department plans to establish once the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756403","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-18","<p>Projects delivered under the One Public Estate programme deliver a range of benefits, including the creation of jobs. To attribute a benefit to the programme, an OPE partnership must submit evidence that a benefit has been delivered. For example, the evidence base for the creation of jobs can include:</p><p>1) an economic impact assessment supporting a planning application</p><p>2) a construction plan</p><p>3) an extract from the tender for a building contract</p><p>This is not an exhaustive list of suitable evidence. One Public Estate works with OPE partnerships to use the most suitable means of determining jobs created, dependent on the nature of individual projects.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-18T13:17:12.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756403/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756403/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756403/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to figure 7 on page 24 of the National Audit Office's report, Progress on the government estate strategy (HC 1131), published on 25 April 2017, what the evidential basis is for the number of jobs created.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8271"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756404","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The figure is based on the Warehouse, Storage &amp; Depots portfolio strategy and refers to potential benefits arising from implementing a networked logistics capability for EA that would result in a consolidated number of depots, and more intensive use of capital equipment. This strategy is being further developed with departments.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T13:49:56.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756404/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756404/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756404/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to figure 16 on page 44 of the National Audit Office's report, Progress on the government estate strategy (HC 1131), published on 25 April 2017, what the evidential basis is for the £40 million in savings made from the reduction in Environment Agency depot costs.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8272"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756405","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The figure illustrates the potential savings from expert advisory services on large portfolios, such as the custodial estate. Savings are based on realising 1% of the in-scope portfolio value based on data from Government’s e-PIMs system. This strategy is being further developed with departments.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T13:57:39.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756405/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756405/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756405/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Ministry of Justice: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to figure 16 on page 44 of the National Audit Office's report, Progress on the government estate strategy (HC 1131), published on 25 April 2017, how the speculative figure of £62 million in savings from the Ministry of Justice custodial estate was calculated by the Government Property Unit.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8273"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756406","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-19","<p>The Government Hubs Programme will consolidate office space in locations with a<br>significant Civil Service presence.</p><p>The location of a strategic hub is based on rigorous criteria including excellent connections<br>to a range of local and national public transport options to ensure that it is accessible.</p><p>Moreover, they are chosen in consultation with the major departmental occupiers planned<br>for that Hub, to ensure that it meets their workforce and operational requirements.</p><p>The percentages quoted in the NAO report were based on GPU’s assessment, at the time,<br>of the proposed capacity of a new hub and the number of staff based in offices within a 10-<br>and 25-mile radius of the city centres (where Hubs are planned to be).</p><p>Moreover, the locations are chosen in consultation with the major departmental occupiers<br>planned for that Hub, to ensure that it meets their workforce and operational requirements.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-19T10:44:51.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756406/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756406/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756406/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how the Government Property Unit calculated that 75 per cent of staff will relocate to a hub less than 10 miles from their current office and that 90 per cent will relocate within 25 miles, as set out in the National Audit Office report Progress on the government estate strategy.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756407","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The latest iteration of the Hubs programme business case was approved by HMT in July 2017. An Outline Business Case for the New Property Model was approved by HMT in January 2017. A full business case for the New Property Model is currently being prepared for review and approval during third quarter of FY2017/18</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T14:11:59.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756407/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756407/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756407/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Property Unit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Government Property Unit has produced a full business case for the (a) Hubs programme and (b) New Property Model.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756408","Cabinet Office","true","2017-10-19","<p><ins class="ministerial"><strong>The Government has a target to release land for at least 160,000 homes in England from the central government estate by 2020.</strong></ins></p><p><del class="ministerial">The Cabinet Office has indicated that it will not be possible to answer this question within the usual time period. An answer is being prepared and will be provided as soon as it is available.</del></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-19T11:49:39.407Z","2017-11-29T12:23:41.51Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756408/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756408/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756408/answer","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756408/answer/previousversion/16158","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether his Department has a target for the number of homes to be built on disposed of Government estate assets.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756409","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>Cabinet Office, DfID &amp; BEIS are participants during the Shadow Running period of the New Property Model.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T14:13:41.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756409/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756409/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756409/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will list the Government departments that participated in the live trials of the New Property Model.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756410","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>Shadow running of the Government Property Agency is currently underway to test and trial processes and systems prior to Go-Live to ensure it has the capacity and capability to deliver. This includes undergoing robust governance and assurance processes which will inform the Go-Live decision.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T14:22:44.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756410/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756410/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756410/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what plans he has to publish the results of the Government Property Unit's live trials of the New Property Model.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756411","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>We anticipate each strategic hub to take up to two years to be ready for occupation. The timescales will vary depending on whether the hub is an existing building requiring refurbishment or a new build to be fitted out.</p><p>We have announced eight government hubs that will be ready for occupation by 2020.</p><p>The strategic hubs will be rolled out in controlled phases, across the UK, to meet future departmental workforce predictions. Departments begin moving to <a href="https://maps.google.com/?q=10+South+Colonnade&amp;entry=gmail&amp;source=g" target="_blank">10 South Colonnade</a>, Canary Wharf, in phases, from September 2017 to September 2018.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T14:08:44.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756411/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756411/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756411/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the timetable is for the completion of each strategic hub in the Government's estate strategy.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8205"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756412","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The overarching framework of the charging mechanism is currently in development with input from HMT and Finance colleagues in Departments. The exact mechanism is being be tailored to the requirements and the nature of the individual departments. This will be an ongoing process. By its very nature the charging mechanism will be commercial in confidence and not intended for publication but will conform to relevant HMT guidelines.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T13:51:52.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756412/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756412/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756412/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, when he plans to publish the new charging mechanism for the New Property Model.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8207"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756413","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-23","<p>Workforce planning is primarily the responsibility of each department to determine based<br>on their individual operational and policy requirements. Each department has their own<br>spending agreements with HM Treasury and are responsible for ensuring they have the<br>right workforce and capability in place to deliver their commitments. It will be for each<br>department to monitor recruitment and turnover within the regional hubs</p><p>Plans are in place for the creation of multi-departmental government Hubs in strategic<br>locations outside London, which will further consolidate our office estate, whilst helping to<br>attract and retain staff by stronger collaboration between departments and enabling staff to<br>grow careers locally.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-23T14:53:04.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756413/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756413/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756413/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether he plans to make an assessment of the effect of relocating staff to regional hubs on (a) staff turnover and (b) available expertise.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756414","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The National Property Control Policy encourages organisations to engage with the Cabinet Office before a formal expenditure submission request is made to increase effectiveness of controls and produce a quicker turnaround time. As such the proportion of applications ultimately rejected is low as these are flushed out before an application is made.</p><p> </p><p>Since 1 April 2016, 126 applications have been received and of these 2 have ultimately been rejected following full engagement. A rejection rate between 1-2% is typical for prior years.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T14:26:47.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756414/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756414/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756414/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many and what proportion of applications made to the Government Property Unit to renew or extend leases have been rejected in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756415","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The National Property Control Policy encourages organisations to engage early with the Cabinet Office. The proportion of applications for approval of expenditure received retrospectively is low.</p><p> </p><p>Since 1 April 2016, 126 applications have been received and of these GPU are aware of 3 which were received after the lease event. A rate between 2-3% for retrospective approval is likely typical for prior years.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T14:24:24.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756415/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756415/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756415/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many and what proportion of applications for lease renewals or extensions made to the Government Property Unit are after the specified time in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756416","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government Property Unit meets with departmental heads of estates on a formal basis regularly and additionally there are many routine contacts on operational business. The Government Property Unit runs a governance board attended by departmental Property Leaders every two months. They further meet individual Departments for bilateral meetings at regularly agreed intervals throughout the year, the frequency being dependent on the size and significance of an individual Department's property portfolio.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T11:09:18.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756416/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756416/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756416/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Property Unit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many times the Government Property Unit met with the head of estates in each Department in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756417","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>Like all major government programmes and projects, the Government Hubs Programme has internal reporting procedures to monitor against Programme plans and benefits and is also subject to possible parliamentary scrutiny.</p><p>Annually, the Government publishes The State of the Estate report which includes the cost of running the estate. There are no plans to change this arrangement.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T13:55:02.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756417/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756417/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756417/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if the Government Property Unit will require each strategic hub to (a) monitor and (b) publish the costs and savings they achieve.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756418","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Cabinet Office is committed to ensuring that contractors and their staff have a sound awareness of cyber risk matters and they take all necessary safeguards to protect the department’s information.</p><p>Cyber security awareness, the need to ensure contractual compliance with Information Assurance standards such as ISO 27001:2013 certification and “Cyber Essentials/ Plus” is specified in contract specifications and reviewed as part of the evaluation process. Contractors must comply with the department’s IT security policies and procedures.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T14:34:22.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756418/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756418/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756418/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Cabinet Office: Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the principle set out in paragraph 5.3.6 of the Government's Cyber Security Strategy that everyone who works in government has a sound awareness of cyber risk applies to members of staff employed by contractors doing work procured by his Department.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756419","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>As set out in the Business Appointment Rules, the independent Advisory Committee on Business Appointments (ACOBA) publish the advice they have given, once they are notified an appointment or employment has been taken up by the applicant or announced publicly. This information can be found here <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/advisory-committee-on-business-appointments" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/advisory-committee-on-business-appointments</a>.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>However the specific information requested is not held centrally and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-09-07T15:14:22.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756419/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756419/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756419/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Business Appointments Advisory Committee: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many letters published on the Acoba website were published there more than one month after being sent in (a) the past 12 months and (b) each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7702"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756420","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The following data relates to competitive tenders for contracts and framework agreements above the OJEU threshold run by the Crown Commercial Service up to 6 September 2017:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>3-6 months</p></td><td><p>6-12 months</p></td><td><p>1-2 years</p></td><td><p>over 2years</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>11</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>15</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>17</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>22</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017-18 (to date)</p></td><td><p>12</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T13:05:45.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756420/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756420/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756420/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Crown Commercial Service: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many procurements undertaken in the last five years by the Crown Commercial Service have taken longer than (a) three months, (b) six months, (c) one year and (d) two years to let.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7703"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756421","Attorney General","false","2017-09-12","<p>The HM Procurator General and Treasury Solicitor Annual Report and Accounts 2016-17 which covers the expenditure of GLD, AGO and HMCPSI, discloses that expenditure on consultants has been kept to a minimum, with spend in 2016-17 of £7k. This figure relates to the cost of professional advice provided to HMCPSI, which was all on a daily rate.</p><p>The Serious Fraud Office (SFO) has not employed any consultants within the past financial year or during the current year.</p><p>The CPS has not procured consultancy services during 2016/17 or during 2017/18 to date.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2017-09-12T07:38:11.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756421/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756421/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756421/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-09-04","Attorney General: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what proportion of consultancy assignments procured by the Law Officers' Departments are paid at a daily rate.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7924"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756422","Attorney General","false","2017-09-19","<p>Requests for temporary staff to be appointed within agreed budgetary provision in the CPS are not required to be accompanied by a formal business case within the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS). Requests for consultancy staff do require a formal business case within the CPS.</p><p>The Serious Fraud Office (SFO) has not employed any consultants within the past financial year or during the current year. Spend on consultants would require a business case setting out the need for such expenditure to the SFO Finance and HR teams. Requests for temporary staff are agreed when the SFO budget is set at the beginning of the financial year. Any additional temporary recruitment during the year is dependent on discussions with the SFO Finance team and Human Resource team, and on occasion the Chief Operating Officer and would require a business case.</p><p>At GLD, HMCPSI and the AGO, agency workers are engaged through Civil Service contractual arrangements to cover short term vacancies and to secure specific specialist legal and support skills that are not available in-house. For that reason, a formal business case is not normally required, unless it is for new posts where agreement is required to increase the headcount in that business area to support a project to improve the department. The approval mechanism for consultancy spend is not via a resources board although a request for consultancy would need to be accompanied by a business justification.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2017-09-19T12:11:45.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756422/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756422/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756422/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-09-04","Attorney General: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, whether requests for consultancy and temporary staff for the Law Officers' Departments must be accompanied by a formal business case.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7945"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756423","Attorney General","false","2017-09-19","<p>During 2016/17 no requests for consultancy or temporary staff for the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) have been considered by a ‘resource board’.</p><p>The SFO also does not approve any expenditure for consultants or temporary workers via a resource board.</p><p>The Government Legal Department (GLD) engages temporary staff through Civil Service contractual arrangements to cover short term vacancies and to secure specific specialist legal and support skills that are not available in-house. It does not use a resource board to approve this form of appointments. Rather, the department’s annual budget for staffing is agreed each year by the GLD Board and formal delegations are made to individual budget holders who then have responsibility for the recruitment and deployment of staff (including temporary staff, where appropriate) within central guidelines. The approval mechanism for consultancy spend at the GLD is not via a resources board although a request for consultancy would need to be accompanied by a business justification. However, there was no consultancy spend in GLD during the last financial year.</p><p>The AGO have not employed any consultancy or agency staff during 2016/17.</p><p>Her Majesty’s Crown Prosecution Service Inspectorate (HMCPSI) discusses and authorises all requests for consultants or temporary staff at their strategic board.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2017-09-19T11:40:54.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756423/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756423/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756423/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-09-04","Attorney General: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what proportion of requests for consultancy and temporary staff for the Law Officers' Departments were approved via a resource board.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7966"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756424","Attorney General","false","2017-09-19","<p>The Law Officers’ Departments are committed to the benefits that can be brought for the taxpayer in the delivery of Government objectives from interchange and is always looking for opportunities to develop arrangements which further the delivery agenda of the Department.</p><p>It is the policy across the Civil Service that where individuals transfer temporarily between our department and another department they move on a loan basis.</p><p>A temporary move to, or from, an organisation outside the Civil Service is referred to as a Secondment and must be for a minimum of 12 months and normally not exceed two years. Therefore, secondment applications, by definition, will not be received from existing civil servants.</p><p>The information requested is only available for the CPS from 2014/15 when the current civil service recruitment system was introduced.</p><p>Number of applications received for internal loans from civil servants:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial year</p></td><td><p>Civil servant applications</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>90</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>46</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>130</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017/18</p></td><td><p>68</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>In the years since 2010 the SFO has had the following numbers of civil servants on loan from and to other government departments.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Number of staff on loan from other government departments</p></td><td><p>Number of SFO staff on loan to other government departments</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017/18</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>9</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>In relation to the Attorney General’s Office (AGO), the Government Legal Department (GLD) and Her Majesty’s Crown Prosecution Service Inspectorate (HMCPSI), the following table shows <em>the number of applications</em> for posts that have been advertised to be filled on loan within the Civil Service since April 2012, which is the earliest date for which records are available. GLD specifically does not hold information prior to 1 April 2014 as information on individual recruitment exercises is not required to be held for more than two years.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>AGO</p></td><td><p>GLD</p></td><td><p>HMCPSI</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/2013</p></td><td><p>21</p></td><td><p>No information available</p></td><td><p>No information available</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/2014</p></td><td><p>78</p></td><td><p>No information available</p></td><td><p>17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/2015</p></td><td><p>145</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/2016</p></td><td><p>241</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/2017</p></td><td><p>124</p></td><td><p>11</p></td><td><p>21</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>01/04/2017 to date</p></td><td><p>211</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2017-09-19T11:44:03.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756424/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756424/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756424/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-09-04","Attorney General: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many applications the Law Officers' Department has received for (a) internal loans and (b) secondments from civil servants in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7987"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756425","Attorney General","false","2017-09-19","<p>The Government Property Unit (GPU) has commissioned Strategic Asset Management Plans (SAMPs) from departments on an annual basis since 2014. The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) and Serious Fraud Office (SFO) are covered as part of the Ministry of Justice’s asset plan.</p><p>The AGO, GLD and HMCPSI are smaller government departments with limited property assets. As such, they have not been commissioned to prepare a SAMP. Information about their property interests is available in their Annual Reports and Accounts and recorded on the GPU property database (EPIMS).</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2017-09-19T11:39:14.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756425/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756425/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756425/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-09-04","Attorney General: Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, in which of the last 10 years the Law Officers' Departments have submitted a strategic asset management plan to the Government Property Unit.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8008"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756426","Attorney General","false","2017-09-13","<p>The policy set out in paragraph 5.3.6 of the National Cyber Security Strategy applies to everyone employed by the Law Officers’ Departments, including contractors. The Law Officers’ Departments are committed to ensuring that contractors and their staff have a sound awareness of cyber risk matters and they take all necessary safeguards to protect the department’s information.</p><p>Cyber security awareness, the need to ensure contractual compliance with Information Assurance standards such as ISO 27001:2013 certification and “Cyber Essentials/ Plus” is included in contract specifications and reviewed as part of the evaluation process. Contractors must comply with the department’s IT security policies and procedures.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2017-09-13T15:43:16.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756426/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756426/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756426/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-09-04","Attorney General: Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, whether the principle set out in paragraph 5.3.6 of the Government's Cyber Security Strategy that everyone who works in government has a sound awareness of cyber risk applies to members of staff employed by contractors doing work procured by the Law Officers' Departments.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756427","Attorney General","false","2017-09-13","<p>The UK’s relationship with the EU's agencies upon exit will be evaluated in light of delivering the twelve objectives outlined by the Prime Minister to achieve a deep and special partnership between the UK and the EU. The UK’s future relationship with the EU's decentralised bodies after leaving the EU is a matter for the negotiations.</p><p>Prior to any decisions on establishing new agencies, the Government will, however, always look to minimise disruption and costs, which will include considering alternative options.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2017-09-13T15:38:51.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756427/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756427/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756427/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-09-04","Attorney General: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what estimate he has made of the number of new arms-length bodies the Law Officers' Departments plan to establish once the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8235"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756428","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>One Public Estate was allocated £6m at Summer Budget 2015 to expand the programme. A further £31m was allocated at Autumn Statement 2015 (£13m in 16/17 and £18m in 17/18) to expand the programme even further, aiming to reach 95% of councils in England by March 2018.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T11:47:55.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756428/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756428/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756428/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","One Public Estate Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much funding has been allocated to the One Public Estate programme in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756429","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>We aim to create around 18 - 22 strategic hubs across the UK by 2023. The exact number and location of each hub will be subject to future departmental workforce predictions.</p><p>We have announced eight government hubs that will be ready for occupation by 2020.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T13:48:34.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756429/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756429/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756429/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the timetable is for the Government Property Unit to establish the regional hubs.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756430","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government Property Unit and the shadow Government Property Agency have a planned approach to the technical skills needed in their roles, aligned to the Government Property Profession competencies. They operate a balanced economy of interim and permanent resource to address particular peaks/specialist skills and ongoing work required. A dedicated budget for staff learning and development is also in place, linked to personal performance objectives and underpinned by a technical and general skills curriculum.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T14:02:10.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756430/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756430/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756430/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Property Unit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what plans he has to increase the amount of property-management expertise available to the Government Property Unit.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8258"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756431","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>Any decision to invest in surplus property for disposal or relet will be made on a case by case basis and will also take into account funding available from the Department or the arm’s length bodies concerned, if it provides value for money.</p><p> </p><p><strong></strong><br><br></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T13:58:25.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756431/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756431/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756431/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether he plans to ask for funding from the public purse for his Department or any of its arm's-length bodies to invest in surplus property for disposal or re-let.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756432","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-27","<p>The Government Propery Unit monitors the performance of large offices across the Civil Service and the proportion by area, of those in 2015-16 is show in the attached.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-27T09:53:04.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756432/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756432/answer","Benchmarked Estate Tenure Types - example.docx","Attachment","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756432/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what proportion of the Government Estate is (a) freehold, (b) leasehold and (c) private finance initiative-managed.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756433","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The state of the estate report 2015-16 contains property cost per FTE by department (in Appendix G) and the regional breakdown is set out below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Region</p></td><td><p>Property cost* per FTE in 2015-16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East Midlands</p></td><td><p>£3,700</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East of England</p></td><td><p>£3,730</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>London</p></td><td><p>£7,920</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North East</p></td><td><p>£2,660</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North West</p></td><td><p>£3,444</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Northern Ireland</p></td><td><p>£3,864</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Scotland</p></td><td><p>£3,944</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South East</p></td><td><p>£3,993</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South West</p></td><td><p>£2,909</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wales</p></td><td><p>£3,472</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>West Midlands</p></td><td><p>£3,613</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Yorkshire and the Humber</p></td><td><p>£3,565</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>* Property cost is the sum of the following costs: Rental Value, Net Unitary Charge, Net Rental Value, Rates, and Total Operational Costs. Figures are derived from data supplied by Departments.<strong> </strong></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T14:05:29.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756433/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756433/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756433/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the cost per head is of the office space used by the Government Estate, by region of the UK.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756434","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Government Property Unit has an organisational structure and staffing complement designed to meet its delivery objectives. It has recently been through a period of recruitment to ensure it has the correct balance of technical and generalist skills. The Unit makes use of a mixed economy of interim and permanent resource to manage demand and access to specialist skills.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-13T14:20:42.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756434/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756434/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756434/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Property Unit: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of the adequacy of staffing in the Government Property Unit.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8257"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756435","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-18","<p><strong>A full business case which contains the financial benefits is currently being developed and has yet to be agreed.</strong></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-18T13:19:20.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756435/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756435/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756435/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to page 44 of the National Audit Office's report, Progress on the government estate strategy, HC1131, published on 25 April 2017, what the range of smaller initiatives is that is intended to bring financial benefits in the New Property Model by the Government Property Unit; and what the estimated financial benefit is of each such initiative.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756436","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>Shadow running of the Government Property Agency is currently underway to test and trial processes and systems prior to Go-Live to ensure it has the capacity and capability to deliver. This includes undergoing robust governance and assurance processes which will inform the Go-Live decision.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T13:57:01.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756436/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756436/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756436/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether his Department is on track to launch the Government Property Agency in September 2017.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756437","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>GPU records the conditions attached to agreement for lease extensions and renewals in the approval issued to departments for expenditure as part of the operation of the National Property Control.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T14:42:05.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756437/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756437/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756437/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Government Property Unit keeps a record of the conditions attached to agreements to extend or renew lets with Government Departments.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756438","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>One Public Estate started as a pilot programme in 2013. Programme running costs have increased each year in line with the programme’s expansion, as detailed in the table below. Programme running costs in 2013/14 - 2016/17 totalled £3,249,471.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> Programme Running Costs</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013-14</strong></p></td><td><p>£191,710</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014-15</strong></p></td><td><p>£411,998</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2015-16</strong></p></td><td><p>£738,822</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2016-17</strong></p></td><td><p>£1,906,941</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Sub Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£3,249,471</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2017-18 </strong><em>(forecast</em>)</p></td><td><p>2,026,922</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T14:02:12.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756438/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756438/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756438/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","One Public Estate Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the running costs of the One Public Estate programme were in each year since that programme started.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756439","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government Communication Service (GCS) is the professional body for people working in communication roles across Government. Records containing the information requested in these Questions are not held centrally and replies would incur disproportionate costs.</p><p> </p><p>The GCS aims to deliver world-class public service communications that support Government priorities, enable the efficient and effective operation of public services and improve people’s lives.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","8382","2017-09-12T13:17:03.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756439/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756439/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756439/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Communication Service: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many civil servants are employed by the Government Communication Service.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8384"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756440","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Committee on Standards in Public Life is an independent, advisory, standing body sponsored by the Cabinet Office. The Committee sets its own work programme. The Committee on Standards in Public Life is following up its 2014 report on Ethical Standards for Public Service Providers and 2015 guidance</p><p>(<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/336942/CSPL_EthicalStandards_web.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/336942/CSPL_EthicalStandards_web.pdf</a>).</p><p> </p><p>As part of its research, the Committee has met with organisations that provide public services, some commissioners and other think tanks and groups interested in this topic.</p><p> </p><p>Attendees at the roundtable on 20 March 2017 were the Association of Chief Executives of Voluntary Organisations, Institute of Business Ethics, Institute for Government, National Council for Voluntary Organisations, Federation of Small Businesses, Public Services Lab, Business Services Association, CBI, Centre for Public Scrutiny and the General Pharmaceutical Council.</p><p> </p><p>The Committee intends to publish its follow up report later this year.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","7546 ; 7547 ; 7548","2017-09-07T15:13:18.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756440/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756440/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756440/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Committee on Standards in Public Life","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, who was present at the roundtable of public service providers hosted by the Committee on Standards in Public Life on 20 March 2017; what was discussed at that meeting; and what work arose as a result of that meeting.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756441","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Department does not centrally hold records extending back to the date specified; gathering this data could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T14:40:34.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756441/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756441/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756441/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many applications for approval to appoint consultants for assignments that extend beyond nine months have been refused since 2015.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756442","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T14:32:58.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756442/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756442/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756442/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what proportion of consultancy contracts procured through Crown Commerical Service agreements were awarded on a fixed-price basis in each year since 2015.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756443","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>A total of 14,244 applications were received in October 2016 for the last round of fast stream graduate applications.</p><p>A total of 2203 applications were received in early 2017 for the last round of commercial fast track apprentice applications.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","7555","2017-09-12T14:39:01.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756443/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756443/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756443/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many commercial fast track apprenticeship applications the Government commercial function received in the last round of applications.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756444","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>A total of 14,244 applications were received in October 2016 for the last round of fast stream graduate applications.</p><p>A total of 2203 applications were received in early 2017 for the last round of commercial fast track apprentice applications.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","7554","2017-09-12T14:39:01.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756444/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756444/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756444/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Civil Servants: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many commercial fast stream graduate applications the Government commercial function received in the last round of applications.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756445","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government Commercial Function is staffed by employees working across many Civil Service Departments. Records containing the detail requested in these questions are not held centrally and replies to these questions would incur disproportionate costs.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Government Commercial Function (GCF) is a cross-government network of around 4,000 civil servants procuring (or supporting the procurement of) goods and services for the government. It also consists of commercial experts who support departments in managing key commercial contracts, and planning for future commercial needs.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","7557 ; 7558 ; 7559","2017-09-12T10:36:23.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756445/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756445/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756445/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Civil Servants: Personal Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many personnel loans from other parts of the Civil Service there have been into the Government commercial function since it was established.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756446","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government Commercial Function is staffed by employees working across many Civil Service Departments. Records containing the detail requested in these questions are not held centrally and replies to these questions would incur disproportionate costs.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Government Commercial Function (GCF) is a cross-government network of around 4,000 civil servants procuring (or supporting the procurement of) goods and services for the government. It also consists of commercial experts who support departments in managing key commercial contracts, and planning for future commercial needs.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","7556 ; 7558 ; 7559","2017-09-12T10:36:23.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756446/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756446/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756446/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Civil Servants: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many secondments there have been from inside the Government commercial function to outside bodies since it was established.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756447","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government Commercial Function is staffed by employees working across many Civil Service Departments. Records containing the detail requested in these questions are not held centrally and replies to these questions would incur disproportionate costs.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Government Commercial Function (GCF) is a cross-government network of around 4,000 civil servants procuring (or supporting the procurement of) goods and services for the government. It also consists of commercial experts who support departments in managing key commercial contracts, and planning for future commercial needs.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","7556 ; 7557 ; 7559","2017-09-12T10:36:23.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756447/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756447/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756447/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many secondments there have been from outside the Government into the Government commercial function since it was established.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756448","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government Commercial Function is staffed by employees working across many Civil Service Departments. Records containing the detail requested in these questions are not held centrally and replies to these questions would incur disproportionate costs.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Government Commercial Function (GCF) is a cross-government network of around 4,000 civil servants procuring (or supporting the procurement of) goods and services for the government. It also consists of commercial experts who support departments in managing key commercial contracts, and planning for future commercial needs.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","7556 ; 7557 ; 7558","2017-09-12T10:36:23.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756448/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756448/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756448/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Crown Commercial Service: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many Crown commerical function members of staff are at each pay grade within the Civil Service.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756449","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-16","<p>Basic cyber security awareness is an essential protection against attacks such as email phishing and departments are already providing training for their staff on this. Government is also developing a security culture strategy to enable civil servants to help counter a range of security risks. In addition, the National Cyber Security Centre’s new Active Defence Measures will ensure that government systems have increased protection from phishing and other cyber attacks.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-16T10:08:51.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756449/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756449/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756449/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of the level of risk to Government cyber-security of human error by civil servants.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756450","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>Contractors working for Government departments are subject to the same security standards and training as civil servants depending on their access to government systems and information. Basic cyber security awareness is an essential protection against attacks such as email phishing and departments are already providing training for their staff and contractors on this. In addition, the National Cyber Security Centre’s new Active Defence Measures will ensure that government systems have increased protection from phishing and other cyber attacks.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T10:04:20.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756450/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756450/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756450/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of the risk posed to Government cyber-security of human error by staff contracted from private sector firms working for Government departments.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756451","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Civil Service Workforce Plan 2016 - 2020 includes an action to pilot alternative approaches to competency based recruitment and promotion in the Civil Service.</p><p> </p><p>A number of pilots across departments are already underway. Once completed, these approaches will be evaluated for implementation across the Civil Service.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T13:19:53.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756451/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756451/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756451/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Civil Servants: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Government has started the pilots for alternative approaches to competency-based recruitment in the civil service as set out in the Government's Civil Service Workforce Plan 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756452","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Mystery Shopper Service aims to complete investigations into Central Government procurements within two months, and those into wider public sector procurements within three months. However, the service is dependent on both suppliers and contracting authorities responding in a timely manner, and investigations sometimes require extended communications to determine the facts. Furthermore, suppliers raising cases sometimes come back with follow up questions or to dispute answers provided, resulting in cases taking longer to resolve than hoped.</p><p> </p><p>The following table shows the number of cases that have exceeded the target timescale up to 6 September 2017:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Exceeding 2 months for Central Government</p></td><td><p>Exceeding 3 months for Wider Public Sector</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>27 (48%)</p></td><td><p>44 (100%)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>26 (59%)</p></td><td><p>64 (57%)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>27 (46%)</p></td><td><p>39 (35%)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>23 (40%)</p></td><td><p>26 (27%)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>19 (56%)</p></td><td><p>36 (42%)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>28 (88%)</p></td><td><p>38 (39%)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017-18 (to date)</p></td><td><p>13 (43%)</p></td><td><p>2 (6%)</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","7606","2017-09-12T10:24:00.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756452/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756452/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756452/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Public Sector: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many and what proportion of mystery shopper investigations into central Government bodies have been conducted within the two month timeline for each year since the service was established.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756453","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Mystery Shopper Service aims to complete investigations into Central Government procurements within two months, and those into wider public sector procurements within three months. However, the service is dependent on both suppliers and contracting authorities responding in a timely manner, and investigations sometimes require extended communications to determine the facts. Furthermore, suppliers raising cases sometimes come back with follow up questions or to dispute answers provided, resulting in cases taking longer to resolve than hoped.</p><p> </p><p>The following table shows the number of cases that have exceeded the target timescale up to 6 September 2017:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Exceeding 2 months for Central Government</p></td><td><p>Exceeding 3 months for Wider Public Sector</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>27 (48%)</p></td><td><p>44 (100%)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>26 (59%)</p></td><td><p>64 (57%)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>27 (46%)</p></td><td><p>39 (35%)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>23 (40%)</p></td><td><p>26 (27%)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>19 (56%)</p></td><td><p>36 (42%)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>28 (88%)</p></td><td><p>38 (39%)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017-18 (to date)</p></td><td><p>13 (43%)</p></td><td><p>2 (6%)</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","7605","2017-09-12T10:24:00.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756453/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756453/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756453/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Public Sector: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many and what proportion of mystery shopper investigations into bodies that are not central government bodies are completed within three months for each year since the service was established.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756454","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>As of 6 September 2017, the Mystery Shopper Service had received 1,261 enquiries of which, 91 have fallen outside the scope of the service’s remit.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T10:11:12.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756454/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756454/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756454/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Public Sector: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many enquiries made to the Government's mystery shopper service were classified as being outside the remit of the service.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756455","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Mystery Shopper Service has investigated the following number of cases related to live procurements up to 6 September 2017:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>26</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>19</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>35</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>29</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>29</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>24</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017-18 (to date)</p></td><td><p>16</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T10:20:36.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756455/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756455/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756455/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Public Sector: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many mystery shopper investigations into live procurements have been conducted for each year since the service was established.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756456","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-14","<p>The majority of Mystery Shopper service users request anonymity. However, with payment cases suppliers are usually willing to waive their right to anonymity in order to resolve the issue promptly.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The exact number of service users requesting anonymity since the service began is not known as this information was not originally recorded.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-14T12:11:51.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756456/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756456/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756456/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Public Sector: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many cases referred to the Government's mystery shopper service requested anonymity.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756457","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>Under the New Property Model, the Government Property Agency is intended to be set up as an Executive Agency of the Cabinet Office. As such, GPA will not be able to accrue any profit from Departments under HMT guidance on Managing Public Money. Any surplus arising will be subject to HMT’s Consolidated Budgeting Guidance rules at the time.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T14:03:57.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756457/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756457/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756457/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of the potential profit the Government Property Unit will accrue from Departments from renting out space at market rates under the New Property Model.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756458","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government Property Unit does not directly manage assets and therefore does not receive any sublet income</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T13:50:23.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756458/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756458/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756458/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Property Unit: Sub-letting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much the Government Property Unit has received from sub-letting in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756459","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>GPU has not directly received any letting fees since 2012. GPU does not act as an intermediary and therefore does not collect letting fees. The unit does not capture data on letting fees collected by departments or third parties.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T14:07:13.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756459/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756459/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756459/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much the Government Property Unit has received in letting fees in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756460","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government Hubs Programme will reduce government buildings from 800 to around 200 by 2023. This 75% reduction in the estate will significantly reduce the overall running costs.</p><p>The Government Hubs will provide modern, flexible office space that can be used more efficiently and innovatively to reduce running costs. The space needed for each civil servant to work will reduce to 6 sq m within strategic hubs, outperforming the current occupation density target of 8 sq m per FTE. Smart working is integral to the Hubs to maximise advances in IT and improve staff wellbeing and productivity.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T13:52:31.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756460/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756460/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756460/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps the Government Property Unit is taking to meet the target of lowering running costs of buildings by 25 per cent through the Hubs programme.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756461","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government Property Unit commissions Strategic Asset Management Plans (SAMPs) from departments on an annual basis. The first commission was in 2014 and there have been three commissions to date. The SAMP articulates the property aspects of a department's business and forms part of the overall planning framework in government linked to each Single Departmental Plan.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T11:07:38.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756461/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756461/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756461/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Cabinet Office: Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, in which of the last 10 years his Department has submitted a strategic asset management plan to the Government Property Unit.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8009"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756462","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>Information about the number of applications received for (a) internal loans and (b) secondments from civil servants in each year since 2010 is not held centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T10:29:13.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756462/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756462/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756462/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Cabinet Office: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many applications his Department has received for (a) internal loans and (b) secondments from civil servants in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7988"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756463","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>From November 2015 until August 2017 all requests to engage consultancy and temporary staff were approved via a governance channel.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T11:10:15.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756463/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756463/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756463/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Cabinet Office: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what proportion of requests for consultancy and temporary staff for his Department were approved via a resource board.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7967"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756464","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>Of the 350 requests for consultancy received through the Cabinet Office consultancy control since the start of 2015, 296 were approved of which 173 included additional conditions. 48 requests were withdrawn.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-13T14:14:52.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756464/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756464/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756464/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many applications for approval to appoint consultants for assignments across Government that extend beyond nine months have been (a) approved with conditions, (b) approved without conditions and (c) withdrawn since 2015.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756465","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>Since November 2015 all requests for consultancy and temporary staff in the department must be accompanied by a formal business case.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T10:43:59.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756465/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756465/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756465/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Cabinet Office: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether requests for consultancy and temporary staff for the his Department must be accompanied by a formal business case.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7947"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756466","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>Since November 2015 all consultancy assignments in the department have been paid at a daily rate. Information prior to this date is not held centrally and could only be provided at a disproportionate cost.</p><p><strong></strong><br><br></p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-12T11:14:25.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756466/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756466/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756466/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Cabinet Office: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what proportion of consultancy assignments procured by his Department are paid at a daily rate.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7925"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756467","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-04","<p>Measuring the cost of problem gambling is a complicated task. The study by The Institute of Public Policy Research “Cards on the Table”, published in December 2016, estimated that the cost to the Government associated with problem gamblers ranged between £260m and £1.16bn. This reflects an estimate of the costs of public services for those individuals, but it does not capture the wider impact of problem gambling and gambling-related harm to the UK economy. The report can be found here: https://about.gambleaware.org/media/1367/cards-on-the-table_dec16.pdf</p><p>GambleAware is commissioning research to improve understanding of gambling-related harm which should lead to a set of metrics which we can use to measure the impact of gambling-related harm on a wider scale. We continue to take problem gambling and gambling-related harm seriously and welcome developments to better understand this issue.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-10-04T12:23:33.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756467/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756467/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756467/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Gambling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate she has made of the cost to the UK economy of problem gambling.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8116"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756468","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-11","<p>The information requested is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-09-11T16:15:00.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756468/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756468/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756468/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Treasury: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what proportion of consultancy assignments procured by his Department are paid at a daily rate.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7941"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756469","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>Requests for approving consultancy and temporary staff do not require a formal business case, but do require justification of the cost and the benefits, and assessment of need before any decision to proceed is taken.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-09-12T10:52:46.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756469/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756469/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756469/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Treasury: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether requests for consultancy and temporary staff for the his Department must be accompanied by a formal business case.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7962"
