"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756514","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Government Property Unit has commissioned Strategic Asset Management Plans (SAMPs) from departments on an annual basis since 2014. The SAMP articulates the property aspects of a department's business and forms part of the overall planning framework in government linked to each Single Departmental Plan. In some cases, where there are significant changes to a department's remit (such as following a machinery of government change or major business reviews), the timing of a SAMP refresh may be aligned with the broader strategy for the department. Information is provided regularly to the Government Property Unit about the management of the department’s property assets and Executive Summaries of SAMPs will be published for the first time in Autumn 2017.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-09T12:12:45.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756514/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756514/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756514/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, in which of the last 10 years her Department has submitted a strategic asset management plan to the Government Property Unit.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8011"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756515","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-12","<p>The UK’s relationship with the EU's agencies upon exit will be evaluated in light of delivering the twelve objectives outlined by the Prime Minister to achieve a deep and special partnership between the UK and the EU. The UK’s future relationship with the EU's decentralised bodies after leaving the EU is a matter for the negotiations.</p><p> </p><p>Prior to any decisions on establishing new agencies, the Government will, however, always look to minimise disruption and costs, which will include considering alternative options.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-09-12T16:56:04.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756515/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756515/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756515/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate she has made of the number of new arms-length bodies her Department plans to establish once the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8238"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756516","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Government is clear that gambling operators must comply with Gambling Commission requirements around Anti-Money Laundering (AML) and Social Responsibility in order to determine the financial capacity of individuals. If they fail to do so they risk sanctions including losing their licence to operate. These requirements include the need to deliver effective customer interactions, particularly in relation to 'high value' customers and those most vulnerable. Operators must also have due regard to Gambling Commission advice around 'Duties and responsibilities under the Proceeds of Crime Act 2002' including the Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements which include knowing a customer's source of funds.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-09-07T14:21:15.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756516/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756516/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756516/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Betting Shops","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, if she will make it her policy to introduce stricter obligations on betting shops to determine the financial capacity of people gambling large sums.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756517","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-04","<p>The policy set out in paragraph 5.3.6 of the National Cyber Security Strategy applies to everyone employed by the Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS), including contractors. DCMS is committed to ensuring contractors and their staff have a sound awareness of cyber risk matters and they take all necessary safeguards to protect the department’s information.</p><p>Cyber security awareness, the need to ensure contractual compliance with Information Assurance standards such as ISO 27001:2013 certification and “Cyber Essentials/ Plus”, is included in contract specifications and reviewed as part of the evaluation process. Contractors must comply with the department’s IT security policies and procedures.</p><p>In addition, DCMS has directed its 43 Arms Length Bodies to gain Cyber Essentials accreditation and is in the process of being certified under the Cyber Essentials scheme through Cabinet Office, for its own supplied IT under the Government Digital Service programme.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-04T11:50:34.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756517/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756517/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756517/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether the principle set out in paragraph 5.3.6 of the Government's Cyber Security Strategy that everyone who works in government has a sound awareness of cyber risk applies to members of staff employed by contractors doing work procured by her Department.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8032"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756518","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-09-12","<p>All contractors who perform work for the Ministry of Defence (MOD) are expected to adhere to relevant policies and procedures in relation to cyber security. This requirement is implemented through legal-standard contractual procedures such as the MOD Procurement Policy Note (09/14) which makes it a mandatory requirement for suppliers of certain contracts to hold Cyber Essentials certification. In 2016, the MOD and Industry agreed to the Defence Conditions (DEFCON) 658 in order to enforce the Cyber Security Model to all new contracts, and, as of 1 October 2017 this shall be further applied to contracts down the supply chain. This thereby allows Defence to mandate cyber security across our supply chain to ensure all staff are meeting this required criteria.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-09-12T13:43:37.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756518/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756518/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756518/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-09-04","Ministry of Defence: Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the principle set out in paragraph 5.3.6 of the Government's Cyber Security Strategy that everyone who works in government has a sound awareness of cyber risk applies to members of staff employed by contractors doing work procured by his Department.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8033"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756519","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Ministry of Defence currently has no plans to establish any new arms-length bodies as a result of the UK leaving the EU.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-09-11T15:45:04.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756519/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756519/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756519/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-09-04","Ministry of Defence: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate he has made of the number of new arms-length bodies his Department plans to establish once the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8239"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756520","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-09-12","<p>The information is not held in the format requested.</p><p>The financial figures quoted in each of the questions do not relate solely to redundancy but to the total staff costs comprising of salaries and wages, social security, pensions, redundancy and severance.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","8369","2017-09-12T13:44:23.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756520/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756520/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756520/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-09-04","Ministry of Defence: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 6 July 2017 to Question 3361 on redundancy, how much of the £2,401,725 paid in redundancy payments to civilian staff in 2016-17 was paid to (a) men and (b) women.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756521","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-09-12","<p>The financial figures quoted in each of the questions are the total staff costs as published in the Ministry of Defence (MOD) Annual Report and Accounts 2016-17 in £000's, and include salaries and wages, social security, pensions, and severance, as well as redundancy payments.</p><p>Of the £12,533 paid in redundancy and severance payments to both Armed Forces and civilian personnel set out in the MOD Annual Report and Accounts 2016-17; £402 was paid to male Armed Forces personnel. No payments were made to female Armed Forces personnel.</p><p>Of the £44,133 paid in redundancy and severance payments to both Armed Forces and civilian personnel set out in the MOD Annual Report and Accounts 2016-17, for the year 2015-16; £9,713 was paid to male Armed Forces personnel and £1,395 was paid to female Armed Forces personnel.</p><p>In line with department policy, values have been rounded to the nearest £000.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","8391","2017-09-12T16:17:47.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756521/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756521/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756521/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-09-04","Ministry of Defence: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 6 July 2017 to Question 3361 on redundancy payments to armed forces staff in 2015-16, how much was paid to (a) men and (b) women.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8368"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756522","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-09-12","<p>The information is not held in the format requested.</p><p>The financial figures quoted in each of the questions do not relate solely to redundancy but to the total staff costs comprising of salaries and wages, social security, pensions, redundancy and severance.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","8370","2017-09-12T13:44:23.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756522/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756522/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756522/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-09-04","Ministry of Defence: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 6 July 2017 to Question 3361 on redundancy, how much of the £2,292,990 paid in redundancy payments to civilian staff in 2015-16 was paid to (a) men and (b) women.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756523","Department for Education","false","2017-09-09","<p>I am sorry, but we are unable to provide that information other than at disproportionate cost.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-09-09T11:59:12.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756523/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756523/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756523/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-04","Department for Education: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of consultancy assignments procured by her Department are paid at a daily rate.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7929"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756524","Department for Education","false","2017-09-12","<p>All expenditure by the department, including on consultants or temporary staff, requires a business case, to be cleared by a Deputy Director, Director or Senior Responsible Officer.</p><p>The Department for Education does not have a resource board.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","7971","2017-09-12T16:35:15.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756524/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756524/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756524/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-04","Department for Education: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether requests for consultancy and temporary staff for the her Department must be accompanied by a formal business case.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7950"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756525","Department for Education","false","2017-09-12","<p>All expenditure by the department, including on consultants or temporary staff, requires a business case, to be cleared by a Deputy Director, Director or Senior Responsible Officer.</p><p>The Department for Education does not have a resource board.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","7950","2017-09-12T16:35:15.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756525/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756525/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756525/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-04","Department for Education: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of requests for consultancy and temporary staff for her Department were approved via a resource board.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7971"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756526","Department for Education","false","2017-09-12","<p>All of the Department’s vacancies that are advertised across the Civil Service are available on inward loan.</p><p> </p><p>I am sorry, but we have only been able to provide data from August 2016, when we changed recruitment provider. We are not able to provide the information prior to August 2016 in the format requested as it would exceed the disproportionate cost threshold as set by Treasury of £850.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of applications from Civil Servants</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>August 2016 – March 2017</p></td><td><p>347</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2017 – to date</p></td><td><p>252</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Secondments are only open to non-civil servants to take up temporary roles in the department. Therefore no civil servants will have applied for secondments.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-09-12T15:10:49.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756526/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756526/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756526/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-04","Department for Education: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many applications her Department has received for (a) internal loans and (b) secondments from civil servants in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7992"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756527","Department for Education","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government Property Unit has commissioned Strategic Asset Management Plans (SAMPs) from departments on an annual basis since 2014. The SAMP articulates the property aspects of a department's business and forms part of the overall planning framework in government linked to each Single Departmental Plan. In some cases, where there are significant changes to a department's remit (such as following a machinery of government change or major business reviews), the timing of a SAMP refresh may be aligned with the broader strategy for the department. Information is provided regularly to the Government Property Unit about the management of the department’s property assets and Executive Summaries of SAMPs will be published for the first time in Autumn 2017.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-09-12T16:34:18.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756527/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756527/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756527/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-04","Department for Education: Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, in which of the last 10 years her Department has submitted a strategic asset management plan to the Government Property Unit.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756528","Department for Education","false","2017-09-09","<p>The Department for Education has no plans to establish any new arms-length bodies once the UK has left the EU.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-09-09T12:00:49.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756528/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756528/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756528/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-04","Department for Education: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the number of new arms-length bodies her Department plans to establish once the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8240"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756529","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Department has submitted a strategic asset management plan to the Government Property Unit for 2014/15, 2015/16 and 2016/17.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-09-11T12:17:09.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756529/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756529/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756529/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-04","Department of Health: Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, in which of the last 10 years his Department has submitted a strategic asset management plan to the Government Property Unit.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756530","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>For the year 2015-16, six women and three men received exit packages.</p><p> </p><p>For 2016-17, 337 women and 240 men received exit packages.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-09-11T13:27:16.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756530/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756530/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756530/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-04","Department of Health: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 6 July 2017 to Question 3364 on redundancy, how much of the exit packages detailed in the Annual Report was paid to (a) men and (b) women in (i) 2015-16 and (ii) 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756531","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Department does not envisage the need to establish new arm’s-length bodies as a result of leaving the European Union.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-09-11T13:28:26.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756531/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756531/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756531/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-04","Department of Health: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of new arms-length bodies his Department plans to establish once the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8243"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756532","Department of Health","false","2017-09-12","<p>The National Cyber Security Strategy 2016-2021 was published in November 2016 by the Minister for the Cabinet Office who has responsibility for cyber security and Government security.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is committed to keeping its systems safe and to protect our data and our networks from attack or interference. All permanent staff, plus contractors or agency staff who work with the Department for three months or more, are expected to undertake a “Responsible for Information” training course that covers cyber security awareness.</p><p> </p><p>When procuring goods and services from third parties, the Department must comply with Procurement Policy Action Note 09/14 published on 25 May 2016 on the Cyber Essentials Scheme, which includes a set of controls which, when properly implemented, provide organisations with basic protection from the most prevalent forms of threat coming from the internet. The Department is able to specify services in a way that best meets its needs and can take further steps to protect data and networks if relevant to the contract in question.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-09-12T14:13:23.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756532/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756532/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756532/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-04","Department of Health: Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether the principle set out in paragraph 5.3.6 of the Government's Cyber Security Strategy that everyone who works in government has a sound awareness of cyber risk applies to members of staff employed by contractors doing work procured by his Department.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8038"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756533","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Department decided to instigate a sale of a majority shareholding in NHS Professionals Ltd in November 2016. The Department received a number of expressions of interest following a successful Open Day and a number of responses to pre-qualification documents from which six bidders were shortlisted.</p><p> </p><p>Although the sale process was not subject to procurement regulations; it was advertised by placing a notice in the Official Journal of the European Union to ensure transparency and also that that as many interested parties as possible were aware of the opportunity.</p><p> </p><p>In a Written Ministerial Statement on 7 September, the Department announced that NHS Professionals will remain in wholly public ownership. After careful consideration, the Government has concluded that none of the offers received for NHS Professionals through the open, rigorous bidding process reflected the company’s growing potential and improved performance.</p><p> </p><p>Since the decision was taken to seek offers, NHS Professionals has significantly increased its performance such that audited profit before tax for the year ended 31 March 2017 was 44% higher than in the previous year. This improvement in financial performance continues to be built upon in the first quarter of the current year. The company’s improved financial and operational performance means it can now invest in improved IT infrastructure, expand its services to the National Health Service and transform into a world-class provider of flexible staff whilst remaining under public ownership – generating further savings for the NHS, all of which will continue to be reinvested in frontline services.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","8365","2017-09-11T13:52:36.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756533/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756533/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756533/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-04","NHS Professionals: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many bids were received for the contract to run the NHS professionals service.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8364"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756534","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Department decided to instigate a sale of a majority shareholding in NHS Professionals Ltd in November 2016. The Department received a number of expressions of interest following a successful Open Day and a number of responses to pre-qualification documents from which six bidders were shortlisted.</p><p> </p><p>Although the sale process was not subject to procurement regulations; it was advertised by placing a notice in the Official Journal of the European Union to ensure transparency and also that that as many interested parties as possible were aware of the opportunity.</p><p> </p><p>In a Written Ministerial Statement on 7 September, the Department announced that NHS Professionals will remain in wholly public ownership. After careful consideration, the Government has concluded that none of the offers received for NHS Professionals through the open, rigorous bidding process reflected the company’s growing potential and improved performance.</p><p> </p><p>Since the decision was taken to seek offers, NHS Professionals has significantly increased its performance such that audited profit before tax for the year ended 31 March 2017 was 44% higher than in the previous year. This improvement in financial performance continues to be built upon in the first quarter of the current year. The company’s improved financial and operational performance means it can now invest in improved IT infrastructure, expand its services to the National Health Service and transform into a world-class provider of flexible staff whilst remaining under public ownership – generating further savings for the NHS, all of which will continue to be reinvested in frontline services.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","8364","2017-09-11T13:52:36.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756534/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756534/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756534/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-04","NHS Professionals: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether the contract to run the NHS professionals service was tendered through a framework agreement.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","8365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756535","Department of Health","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Department does not hold information on the number of applications received for internal loans and secondments. The number of secondees and loan in to the Department in 2016/17 was six. Data is not held for the years 2010/11 to 2015/16.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-09-12T14:52:51.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756535/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756535/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756535/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-04","Department of Health: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many applications his Department has received for (a) internal loans and (b) secondments from civil servants in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7996"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756536","Department of Health","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Department has procedures in place to comply with Cabinet Office Efficiency controls ensuring that all requests for consultancy or temporary staff are subject to approval by formal panels. These panels provide the ultimate approval based upon business case submissions.</p><p> </p><p>We do not recognise the term ‘resource board’, however, the process for approving professional services spend is via a professional services business case (PSBC) that gets approved by the Finance Approvals Panel (FAP). Temporary staff are approved via one of two routes:</p><p> </p><p>- Specialist Contractors = PSBC to secretariat then FAP</p><p> </p><p>- Admin and Clerical = complete a ‘Request to Recruit’ Form (which is a proportionate type of business case) which is then submitted via a secretariat.</p><p> </p><p>With regard to the question on rates, the Department does hold this information on its electronic procurement system from which the proportion of consultants on daily rates could be calculated, however, this would require a review of each individual contract to check the payment method, and would result in disproportionate cost. We are not therefore able to provide this information.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","7933 ; 7954","2017-09-12T14:47:35.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756536/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756536/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756536/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-04","Department of Health: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of requests for consultancy and temporary staff for his Department were approved via a resource board.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7975"
