"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756839","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>General practitioner practices are independent businesses and as such it would be for them to determine for themselves whether or not they offer such incentives as part of their overall management of their business.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-09-11T15:55:30.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756839/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756839/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756839/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-04","General Practitioners: Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether he has undertaken a cost-benefit analysis of allowing GP practices to fund tuition fees for medical students who would join that practice on qualification.","false","Biography information for Iain Stewart","Milton Keynes South","Iain Stewart","8191"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756840","Home Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government has made no assessment of the effectiveness of playing music in public spaces to deter anti-social behaviour. However, the Government has introduced a range of powers in the Anti-social Behaviour, Crime and Policing Act 2014. These powers are flexible and local in nature so that the police and local agencies are able to tackle anti-social behaviour the most effective way locally.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-09-12T14:56:30.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756840/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756840/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756840/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-04","Antisocial Behaviour: Public Places","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent assessment she has made of the efficacy of playing classical music in public spaces to deter anti-social behaviour.","false","Biography information for Iain Stewart","Milton Keynes South","Iain Stewart","8190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756841","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>No minimum threshold is applied for investigating allegations of fraud related to child maintenance by either the Child Support Agency or the Child Maintenance Service, allegations of this kind are considered on a case by case basis.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-09-11T11:45:22.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756841/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756841/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756841/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether the Child Support Agency applies a de minimis limit for investigating allegations of fraud.","false","Biography information for Iain Stewart","Milton Keynes South","Iain Stewart","7846"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756842","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government has no current plans to introduce a Class 3 National Insurance credit for volunteers.</p><p> </p><p>However on 6 September, a Call For Evidence was published on the Full-Time Social Action Review which will develop recommendations on how to support full time volunteering.</p><p> </p><p>Details of how to submit evidence are available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/643612/Full_Time_Social_Action_Review_-_Call_for_Evidence.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/643612/Full_Time_Social_Action_Review_-_Call_for_Evidence.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>The review will consider what the voluntary sector, industry and, if needed, government can do to support full-time volunteering.</p><p> </p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman","8438 ; 8487","2017-09-12T16:02:57.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756842/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756842/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756842/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","National Insurance Contributions: Voluntary Work","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the forthcoming National Insurance Contributions Bill, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of granting Class 3 national insurance credits to young people engaged in full-time social action programmes.","false","Biography information for Michael Tomlinson","Mid Dorset and North Poole","Michael Tomlinson","8437"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756843","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government has no current plans to introduce a Class 3 National Insurance credit for volunteers.</p><p> </p><p>However on 6 September, a Call For Evidence was published on the Full-Time Social Action Review which will develop recommendations on how to support full time volunteering.</p><p> </p><p>Details of how to submit evidence are available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/643612/Full_Time_Social_Action_Review_-_Call_for_Evidence.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/643612/Full_Time_Social_Action_Review_-_Call_for_Evidence.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>The review will consider what the voluntary sector, industry and, if needed, government can do to support full-time volunteering.</p><p> </p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman","8437 ; 8487","2017-09-12T16:02:57.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756843/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756843/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756843/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","National Insurance Contributions: Voluntary Work","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the forthcoming National Insurance Contributions Bill, if =he-she- will consult the Youth Full-Time Social Action Review on the potential merits of granting Class 3 national insurance credits to full-time volunteers.","false","Biography information for Michael Tomlinson","Mid Dorset and North Poole","Michael Tomlinson","8438"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756844","Department for Education","false","2017-09-12","<p>Disabled and non-disabled students alike can apply for loans to help pay for university or college tuition fees and to help with living costs. Some students may also be eligible for additional support where they have children or adults who depend on them. Disabled students can also apply for Disabled Students’ Allowances (DSAs), which are not income assessed and are not repayable, to cover essential, additional, learning-related expenditure they are obliged to incur because of their disability. Information on student support including DSAs is available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/student-finance/extra-help" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/student-finance/extra-help</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-09-12T14:24:54.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756844/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756844/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756844/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-04","Students: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what provision her Department makes to assist with the living costs of disabled students attending university.","false","Biography information for Michael Tomlinson","Mid Dorset and North Poole","Michael Tomlinson","8435"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756845","Department for Education","false","2017-09-12","<p>The interest rates for income contingent student loans are prescribed by secondary legislation. The rates for all three schemes are set annually and apply from 1 September to 31 August the following year. The rates are based on the retail price index (RPI) from the previous March.</p><p> </p><p>Interest rates for student loans in repayment vary with the income of the borrower. Borrowers earning less than £21,000 p.a. are charged interest at RPI only. Interest then increases on a sliding scale with income up to a maximum of RPI+3% for borrowers earning over £41,000.</p><p> </p><p>Government-issued student loans have much more favourable terms than commercial loans, and are subsidised by the Government. Borrowers are protected. Monthly repayments are linked to income and not to the amount borrowed. Borrowers earning less than the repayment threshold of £21,000 repay nothing at all. Borrowers earning above £21,000 repay 9% of their income above the threshold, irrespective of the amount borrowed. Any outstanding loan balance, including interest, is written off after 30 years with no detriment to the borrower. Student loans are available to all eligible students regardless of their previous financial history. The Department is not aware of any commercial loans that offer this level of borrower protection.</p><p> </p><p>This system of variable interest rates based on income is progressive, and ensures that higher earners make a fair contribution to the sustainability of the higher education system. Reducing interest rates would only benefit higher earning borrowers, who would pay back less than they do currently. Low-earning borrowers, who will have a proportion of their debt written off at the end of the loan period, would not benefit from a reduction in rates.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-09-12T12:12:36.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756845/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756845/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756845/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-04","Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, for what reasons interest rates on student loans are set at their present level; and what the potential merits are of lowering those levels.","false","Biography information for Michael Tomlinson","Mid Dorset and North Poole","Michael Tomlinson","8436"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756846","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-07","<p>At 31st August, 216,384 eligibility codes had been issued for 3 year olds that were valid for the September term.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-07T14:57:04.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756846/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756846/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756846/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many eligibility codes for 30 hours of free childcare were generated before the deadline of 31 August 2017.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","8168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756847","Department for Education","false","2017-09-07","<p>The national rollout of 30 hours free childcare marks the delivery of a manifesto commitment that will help hundreds of thousands of hard working families. Over 200,000 valid 30 hours codes have been generated, reaching our target for 1<sup>st</sup> September.</p><p>As of 6<sup>th</sup> September, 152,829 eligibility codes for 30 hours free childcare have been validated. These are eligibility codes that were issued by 31<sup>st</sup> August and validated by 5<sup>th</sup> September for children aged three by 31<sup>st</sup> August 2017.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-09-07T16:03:52.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756847/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756847/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756847/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-04","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many eligibility codes for 30 hours of free childcare have been validated by providers and local authorities.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","8167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756848","Department of Health","false","2017-09-07","<p>My Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State frequently visits trusts across the country and will continue to do so over the next year.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-09-07T09:55:58.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756848/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756848/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756848/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-04","Dewsbury and District Hospital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether he plans to visit Dewsbury and District Hospital in the next 12 months.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","8169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756849","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-07","<p>Child sexual abuse is abhorrent, and victims can apply for taxpayer-funded compensation awards through the Criminal Injuries Compensation Scheme (the Scheme).</p><p> </p><p>The Scheme is made by the Secretary of State under the Criminal Injuries Compensation Act 1995 having been approved by each House of Parliament. The Criminal Injuries Compensation Authority (CICA) administers the Scheme and decides all claims independently of ministers and Parliament. The CICA sets guidelines to assist them in administering the Scheme.</p><p> </p><p>The CICA guidelines are intended to make sure that controlling and abusive behaviour is taken into account when handling compensation applications for child sexual abuse. The CICA are urgently reviewing their guidelines to ensure they are robust enough to deal with cases where grooming may be a factor.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-09-07T14:47:24.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756849/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756849/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756849/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-04","Criminal Injuries Compensation: Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to the letter to him from Barnardo's, Victim Support, Liberty, Rape Crisis and the National Working Group of 18 July 2017, if he will review the Criminal Injuries Compensation Authority Guidelines to ensure that children who are raped or sexually abused are not refused compensation on the grounds that they consented to that rape or abuse.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","7879"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756850","Home Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>138 cats were used for basic research: 24 for cardiovascular blood and lymphatic systems research; 18 for musculoskeletal systems; 24 for endocrine system and metabolism research; one for nervous system research; and, 71 for multisystemic research.</p><p>52 cats were used for translational research into animal diseases and disorders. These animals were used for: studies on domestic cat nutrition and dentistry; investigation of physiology and natural disease and its prevention; and, vaccine studies.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-09-07T09:55:31.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756850/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756850/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756850/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-04","Animal Experiments: Cats","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to Table 4 of the Annual Statistics of Scientific Procedures on Living Animals, Great Britain, 2016, what the experiments carried out on the 190 cats were.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","7633"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756851","Home Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>On 1 January 2013, the Animals (Scientific Procedures) Act 1986 was amended to transpose European Directive 2010/63/EU on the protection of animals used for scientific purposes. The amended legislation does not grant Home Office inspectors entitlement to inspect overseas facilities. The Home Office expects all establishments to exercise due diligence when acquiring non-human primates as set out in the published guidance at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/291350/Guidance_on_the_Operation_of_ASPA.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/291350/Guidance_on_the_Operation_of_ASPA.pdf</a></p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-09-07T09:54:48.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756851/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756851/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756851/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-04","Animal Experiments: Primates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to Table 2.3 of the Annual Statistics of Scientific Procedures on Living Animals, Great Britain, 2016, how her Department ensures that the colonies from which 1,739 primates used for the first time in experimental procedures in 2016 originate are self-sustaining.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","7634"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756852","Home Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>All primates used for the first time in experimental procedures in 2016 were either F2 or greater or from self sustaining colonies.</p><p> </p><p>The Animals (Scientific Procedures) Act 1986 defines a colony of animals as a self sustaining colony if:</p><p>(a) the colony is kept in captivity in a way that ensures the animals are accustomed to humans;</p><p>(b) the colony consists only of animals that have been bred in captivity; and</p><p>(c) the colony is sustained only by animals being bred within the colony or animals being sourced from other colonies that meet paragraphs (a) and (b).</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-09-07T09:55:05.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756852/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756852/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756852/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-04","Animal Experiments: Primates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the primates used in experimental procedures in 2016 were F1, born from wild parents, or F2 greater, born from parents who were also born in captivity; and how she plans to monitor the reduction in F1 primates that should occur if the colonies are truly self-sustaining.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","7635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756853","Home Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>In 2016 652 non-human primates used for the first time in scientific research came from Asia and 1,525 came from Africa.</p><p>The Home Office ensures that animals are only used when necessary and under strict controls which keep suffering to the minimum necessary. Any research that is licensed has undergone a thorough harm-benefit analysis including ensuring that the planned work fully implements the 3Rs (replacement, reduction and refinement).</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-09-07T09:54:17.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756853/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756853/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756853/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-04","Animal Experiments: Primates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many primates used in experiments for the first time in 2016 came from Asia or Africa; and what steps the Government is taking to ensure that there is a reduction in the importation of monkeys for research.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","7630"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756854","Home Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Home Office ensures that animals are only used when necessary and under strict controls which keep suffering to a minimum. Any research which we licence must undergo a thorough harm-benefit analysis including ensuring that the planned work implements the 3Rs (replacement, reduction and refinement).</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-09-07T09:55:21.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756854/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756854/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756854/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-04","Animal Experiments: Primates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government has taken to reduce the use of monkeys in regulatory testing for human medicines since 2016.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","7631"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756855","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>The support that Access to Work provides is considered on a case-by-case basis, dependent on individual work-related needs caused by disability or health conditions. Support can include specialist equipment, which may potentially include a ‘hoist’ if such an item is deemed to be necessary for the individual’s needs and appropriate within the terms of Access to Work guidance.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-12T13:54:18.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756855/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756855/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756855/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Access to Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether hoists are refundable under the Access to Work scheme.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","8356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756856","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions has an obligation to handle public resources to high standards of probity, including standards of accountability and transparency, and this duty requires that there are clear audit trails for transactions involving public funds. In order to meet the necessary standards, we have to ensure that the evidence supporting decisions regarding Access to Work awards is current and relevant.</p><p> </p><p>Access to Work can provide support of up to a maximum of £42,100 per year beyond that which is required from employers as reasonable adjustments. The process of deciding and recording an award requires a number of pieces of evidence, including evidence of what reasonable adjustment has been put in place by an employer.</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-12T14:53:17.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756856/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756856/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756856/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Access to Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, why Access to Work claim forms require certification by an employer or support worker.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","8357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756857","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>The criteria for meeting the Access to Work certification requirement for self-employment are laid out in the Access to Work DWP Staff Guide, which is publicly available on GOV.UK through the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/access-to-work-staff-guide" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/access-to-work-staff-guide</a></p><p>In the current guidance, for Access to Work purposes, a self-employed person is classed as someone who is:</p><ul><li>operating a business either on their own account or in partnership; or working for an employer on a self-employed contractual basis’</li><li>operating a franchised business on a self-employed basis</li><li>running a business that satisfies the past or prospective viability tests (such as achieving a minimum level of turnover each year - this level is currently set at the Lower Earnings Limit (LEL) of £5,824 per annum), and</li><li>possessing a Unique Tax Reference Number (UTR)</li></ul><p>Self-employed people can meet the Access to Work certification requirement by providing a UTR; and either of the following:</p><ul><li>accounts for an established businesses; or,</li><li>a business plan of a standard acceptable to a bank or other financial institution.</li></ul>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-12T14:13:09.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756857/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756857/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756857/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Access to Work Programme: Self-employed","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how self-employed people can meet the Access to Work certification requirement by an employer or support worker.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","8358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756858","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>We have interpreted this question to relate to the current process for making payments to customers.</p><p> </p><p>At present, once an award has been agreed, individual costs are reimbursed retrospectively rather than a single lump sum payment being issued in advance.</p><p> </p><p>We recently conducted a voluntary trial of a cash ‘Personal Budget’ model for Access to Work awards, which tested the response of Access to Work users to more direct control of their awards. We are using evidence from this trial to develop a further trial of personal budgets which we intend to launch shortly.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-12T12:00:26.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756858/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756858/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756858/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Access to Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for what reasons Access to Work claim handlers make separate payments to customers who have multiple such allowances rather than making a single payment.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","8359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756859","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-12","<p>The fire safety requirements currently in place for upholstered furniture and furnishings used in UK homes are being reviewed to ensure they reflect changed fire safety risks, risks associated with exposure to flame retardant chemicals and technological advances. In doing so, public protection remains the Government’s priority.</p><p>We have consulted on proposals for reform and are reviewing options in light of the stakeholder responses received and in light of the Grenfell Tower Fire. We will publish the Government response in due course.</p><p>Local authority trading standards are responsible for checking compliance with and enforcement of the requirements.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-12T15:46:45.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756859/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756859/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756859/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-04","Furniture: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether his Department has made an assessment of (a) the adequacy of and (b) compliance with the fire safety standards of furniture products in the UK; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","7834"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756860","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>During my visit to Hong Kong on 23/24 August, I discussed this case with the Chief Executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region, Carrie Lam. During my meeting, I stressed the UK's commitment to the Sino-British Joint Declaration and 'One Country, Two Systems'. I also made clear that it is essential that Hong Kong enjoys, and is seen to enjoy, the full measure of its high degree of autonomy and commitment to the rule of law enshrined in the Joint Declaration and Basic Law. On 17 August an FCO spokesperson issued a statement on the case, which said that &quot;the UK remains a staunch supporter of the right to peaceful protest and we believe it is vital that Hong Kong's young people have a voice in politics. Hong Kong's way of life is underpinned by its rule of law. We note the decision reached by the Court of Appeal on the case of Joshua Wong, Nathan Law and Alex Chow and we hope the decision on this case will not discourage legitimate protest in the future.&quot;</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-09-12T16:10:42.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756860/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756860/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756860/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-04","Hong Kong: Political Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with the Government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region on the imprisonment of three protestors involved in the pro-democracy Umbrella Movement of 2014.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","7831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756861","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government has undertaken a significant amount of work to assess the economic and fiscal impacts of leaving the EU. This is part of our continuing programme of rigorous and extensive analytical work covering a range of scenarios on a sector by sector basis.</p><p> </p><p>We are seeking the best possible deal for the United Kingdom and the work being done reflects this.</p><p> </p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-12T10:24:50.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756861/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756861/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756861/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will update his Department's analysis of 18 April 2016, published in HM Treasury analysis: the long-term economic impact of EU membership and the alternatives, Cm 9250, on the effect of leaving the EU single market and concluding a trade deal with the EU on public sector receipts.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7833"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756862","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>I refer the Rt Hon. member to the answer I gave on 5th September 2017 to PQ 6058.</p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-09-12T12:07:14.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756862/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756862/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756862/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Cabinet Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, which EU legislation within his Department's responsibilities will (a) be incorporated into UK law through the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill and (b) require to be amended under powers in that Bill.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7905"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756863","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-06","<p>All meetings of Ministers and Permanent Secretaries with external stakeholders are published as part of the Cabinet Office quarterly transparency releases.</p>","Ashford","Damian Green",,"2017-09-06T11:10:59.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756863/answer","Biography information for Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756863/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756863/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Cabinet Office: Legatum Institute","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will publish details of all (a) meetings and (b) telephone calls that have taken place between the Cabinet Secretary and representatives of the Legatum Institue in the last 18 months.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","8423"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756864","Attorney General","false","2017-09-18","<p>The European Union (Withdrawal) Bill will convert European Union law into UK law as it applies in the UK at the moment of exit. This will ensure that, wherever possible, the same rules and laws will apply the day after exit as they did before.</p><p>The Government is still making a detailed assessment of what corrections will be required to make that law function appropriately on exit day. The Government’s current estimate is that we will need to make between 800 and 1,000 statutory instruments to make exit a reality in UK law.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2017-09-18T11:40:33.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756864/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756864/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756864/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-09-04","Attorney General: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, which EU legislation within the Law Officers' Departments' responsibilities will (a) be incorporated into UK law through the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill and (b) require to be amended under powers in that Bill.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7904"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756865","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>The EU Withdrawal Bill will be the primary vehicle for domesticating the financial services regime and ensuring that it can function when the UK leaves the EU. The Bill will also preserve a large body of EU law relating to customs, taxes and anti-money laundering. In the case of customs duty, VAT and excise, the domesticated EU law will be replaced under the Customs Bill.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-12T10:37:38.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756865/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756865/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756865/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Treasury: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, which EU legislation within his Department's responsibilities will (a) be incorporated into UK law through the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill and (b) require to be amended under powers in that Bill.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756866","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-12","<p>The European Union (Withdrawal) Bill will convert European Union law into UK law as it applies in the UK at the moment of exit. This will ensure that, wherever possible, the same rules and laws will apply the day after exit as they did before.</p><p>The Government is still making a detailed assessment of what corrections will be required to make that law function appropriately on exit day. The Government’s current estimate is that we will need to make between 800 and 1,000 statutory instruments to make exit a reality in UK law.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-09-12T15:05:22.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756866/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756866/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756866/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Department for Communities and Local Government: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, which EU legislation within his Department's responsibilities will (a) be incorporated into UK law through the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill and (b) require to be amended under powers in that Bill.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7906"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756867","Department for Education","false","2017-09-12","<p>The European Union (Withdrawal) Bill will convert European Union law into UK law as it applies in the UK at the moment of exit. This will ensure that, wherever possible, the same rules and laws will apply after exit from the EU as they did before.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is still making a detailed assessment of what corrections will be required to make that law function appropriately.</p><p> </p><p>The department is responsible for a number of policy areas falling within the scope of this process including recognition of professional qualifications, equalities and participation in some EU agencies.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-09-12T16:51:45.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756867/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756867/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756867/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-04","Department for Education: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, which EU legislation within her Department's responsibilities will (a) be incorporated into UK law through the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill and (b) require to be amended under powers in that Bill.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7909"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756868","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-08","<p>As part of our dialogue with the Government of Uganda on all aspects of democratic governance and human rights, we continue to stress the importance of resolving disputes fairly, peacefully and with respect for human rights and fundamental freedoms. The UK Government also supports projects in Northern Uganda related to the protection of land rights and community accountability.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-09-08T11:45:38.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756868/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756868/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756868/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-04","Uganda: Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations his Department has made to the Ugandan authorities and the UK's Ugandan High Commissioner on repression and violence in Northern Uganda.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756869","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>​The European Union (Withdrawal) Bill will convert European Union law into UK law as it applies in the UK at the moment of exit. This will ensure that, wherever possible, the same rules and laws will apply the day after exit as they did before.</p><p>The Government is still making a detailed assessment of what corrections will be required to make that law function appropriately on exit day.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-09-12T16:45:06.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756869/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756869/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756869/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-04","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, which EU legislation within his Department's responsibilities will (a) be incorporated into UK law through the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill and (b) require to be amended under powers in that Bill.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7912"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756870","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-12","<p>The European Union (Withdrawal) Bill, published on 13 July, will end the supremacy of EU law in the UK, whilst also ensuring, so far as possible, that the same rules and laws will apply on the day after exit as on the day before. All government departments are currently reviewing the EU laws that apply in their policy areas and how our withdrawal from the EU will affect the operation of those laws. Where laws need to be fixed, the government will ensure this is done through the powers outlined in the Bill.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-12T13:43:51.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756870/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756870/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756870/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-04","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, which EU legislation within his Department's responsibilities will (a) be incorporated into UK law through the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill and (b) require to be amended under powers in that Bill.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7910"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756871","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-12","<p>The European Union (Withdrawal) Bill will convert European Union law into UK law as it applies in the UK at the moment of exit. This will ensure that, wherever possible, the same rules and laws will apply the day after exit as they did before.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is still making a detailed assessment of what changes will be required to make that law function appropriately on exit day. The Government’s current estimate is that we will need to make between 800 and 1,000 statutory instruments to make exit a reality in UK law.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-09-12T16:57:06.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756871/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756871/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756871/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, which EU legislation within her Department's responsibilities will (a) be incorporated into UK law through the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill and (b) require to be amended under powers in that Bill.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7907"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756872","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-09-12","<p>The European Union (Withdrawal) Bill will convert European Union law into UK law as it applies in the UK at the moment of exit. This will ensure that, wherever possible, the same rules and laws will apply the day after exit as they did before.</p><p>The Government is still making a detailed assessment of what corrections will be required to make that law function appropriately on exit day. The Government's current estimate is that we will need to make between 800 and 1,000 statutory instruments to make exit a reality in UK law.</p><p>The only EU-derived domestic legislation within the responsibility of the Ministry of Defence which will continue to have effect through clause 2 of the Bill and require to be amended under powers in that Bill are the Defence and Security Public Contracts Regulations 2011 (SI 2011/1848).</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-09-12T15:50:32.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756872/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756872/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756872/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-09-04","Ministry of Defence: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, which EU legislation within his Department's responsibilities will (a) be incorporated into UK law through the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill and (b) require to be amended under powers in that Bill.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7908"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756873","Department of Health","false","2017-09-12","<p>The European Union (Withdrawal) Bill, published on 13 July 2017, will ensure a smooth and orderly exit from the EU. It also ensures, so far as possible, that the same rules and laws will apply on the day after exit as on the day before. All Government Departments are currently reviewing the EU laws that apply in their policy areas and how withdrawal from the EU will affect the operation of those laws. There are decades of EU law to consider, and we are working to ensure that the statute book works on exit, fixing laws where necessary, and that the maximum possible certainty is provided for individuals and businesses as we leave the EU.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is fully engaged in this legislative process.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-09-12T14:04:19.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756873/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756873/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756873/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-04","Department of Health: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, which EU legislation within his Department's responsibilities will (a) be incorporated into UK law through the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill and (b) require to be amended under powers in that Bill.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7913"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756874","Department for International Development","false","2017-09-11","<p>There is no EU Legislation within my Department’s responsibilities that will be incorporated into UK law through the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill or be required to be amended under the powers within the Bill.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-11T17:00:04.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756874/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756874/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756874/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-04","Department for International Development: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, which EU legislation within her Department's responsibilities will (a) be incorporated into UK law through the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill and (b) require to be amended under powers in that Bill.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7915"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756875","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-12","<p>The European Union (Withdrawal) Bill will convert European Union law into UK law as it applies in the UK at the moment of exit. This will ensure that, wherever possible, the same rules and laws will apply the day after exit as they did before.</p><p>The Government is still making a detailed assessment of what corrections will be required to make that law function appropriately on exit day. The Government’s current estimate is that we will need to make between 800 and 1,000 statutory instruments to make exit a reality in UK law.</p><p>The Ministry of Justice is responsible for EU legislation in fields such as civil and family justice, legal aid, legal services and some aspects of criminal justice.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-09-12T16:06:50.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756875/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756875/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756875/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-04","Ministry of Justice: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, which EU legislation within his Department's responsibilities will (a) be incorporated into UK law through the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill and (b) require to be amended under powers in that Bill.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7917"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756876","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The European Union (Withdrawal) Bill will convert European Union law into UK law as it applies in the UK at the moment of exit. This will ensure that, wherever possible, the same rules and laws will apply the day after exit as they did before.</p><p>The Government is still making a detailed assessment of what corrections will be required to make that law function appropriately on exit day. The Government’s current estimate is that we will need to make between 800 and 1,000 statutory instruments to make exit a reality in UK law.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2017-09-12T16:53:43.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756876/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756876/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756876/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-09-04","Northern Ireland Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, which EU legislation within his Department's responsibilities will (a) be incorporated into UK law through the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill and (b) require to be amended under powers in that Bill.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7918"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756877","Home Office","false","2018-02-21","<p>On 30 November, the Government published data on the numbers of children transferred to the UK from the Calais camp clearance under both the Dublin III Regulation and section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016. The data can be accessed here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/transfers-of-children-to-the-uk-from-the-calais-operation-november-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/transfers-of-children-to-the-uk-from-the-calais-operation-november-2017</a>The Government has committed to publishing regular updates on the number of those transferred under the Dublin III Regulation. This data will be published in the coming months. Eurostat the EU’s statistics agency regularly publishes Member State figures, which can be found at:</p><p><a href="http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/statistics-explained/index.php/Asylum_quarterly_report" target="_blank">http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/statistics-explained/index.php/Asylum_quarterly_report</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The Home Office publishes a range of data on asylum claims from unaccompanied children which can be found at the following link. This data relates to all unaccompanied children who have claimed asylum in the UK and does not provide a breakdown depending on the child’s method of entry.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-july-to-september-2017/how-many-people-do-we-grant-asylum-or-protection-to" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-july-to-september-2017/how-many-people-do-we-grant-asylum-or-protection-to</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-02-21T17:43:54.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756877/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756877/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756877/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-04","Asylum: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to table AS 08 Q of the Quarterly Immigration Statistics, January to March 2017, published on 25 May 2017, how many applications for asylum made during Quarter 1 of 2017 were made by unaccompanied children who arrived in the UK (a) under section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016, (b) through the Dublin III Regulation and (c) by their own initiative.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756878","Home Office","false","2018-02-21","<p>In the Government White Paper on the Repeal Bill [‘Legislating for the United Kingdom’s withdrawal from the European Union’], published on 30 March 2017, we estimated around 800 - 1,000 EU-exit related Statutory Instruments will be required to make the necessary changes to UK law as a whole.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-02-21T17:42:33.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756878/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756878/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756878/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-04","Home Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, which EU legislation within her Department's responsibilities will (a) be incorporated into UK law through the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill and (b) require to be amended under powers in that Bill.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7914"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756879","Wales Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Wales Office has no EU legislation within its responsibilities.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-09-11T10:40:39.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756879/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756879/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756879/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-09-04","Wales Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, which EU legislation within his Department's responsibilities will (a) be incorporated into UK law through the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill and (b) require to be amended under powers in that Bill.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7922"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756880","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>As set out in the Transport Investment Strategy, published in July 2017, the Major Road Network (MRN) will be formed from a middle tier of England’s busiest and most economically important local authority A roads, sitting between England’s Strategic Road Network (SRN) and the local road network. A consultation later this year will include further details regarding what type of regionally and nationally important A roads will be part of the MRN.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-11T12:56:54.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756880/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756880/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756880/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Roads: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether red routes in London will be classified as major roads for the purposes of the new National Road Fund.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","8448"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756881","Scotland Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Scotland Office is not responsible for any EU legislation but is reviewing the UK legislation it is responsible for to establish where corrections are required to take account of our exit from the EU.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-09-12T12:02:12.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756881/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756881/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756881/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-09-04","Scotland Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, which EU legislation within his Department's responsibilities will (a) be incorporated into UK law through the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill and (b) require to be amended under powers in that Bill.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7919"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756882","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-12","<p>The European Union (Withdrawal) Bill will convert European Union law into UK law as it applies in the UK at the moment of exit. This will ensure that, wherever possible, the same rules and laws will apply the day after exit as they did before.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is still making a detailed assessment of what corrections will be required to make that law function appropriately on exit day. The Government’s current estimate is that we will need to make between 800 and 1,000 statutory instruments to make exit effective in UK law.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-12T11:19:22.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756882/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756882/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756882/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Department for Transport: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which EU legislation within his Department's responsibilities will (a) be incorporated into UK law through the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill and (b) require to be amended under powers in that Bill.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756883","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>As set out in the Transport Investment Strategy published in July 2017, the Major Road Network (MRN) – funded by the National Road Fund – will be formed from a middle tier of England’s busiest and most economically important local authority A roads, sitting between England’s Strategic Road Network (SRN) and the local road network. A consultation later this year will include further details regarding what type of regionally and nationally important A roads will be part of the MRN.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-11T12:11:56.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756883/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756883/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756883/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Roads: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the Transport for London Road Network will be eligible for funding from the new National Road Fund.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","8422"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756884","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-09-13","<p>As set out in our position paper on Northern Ireland and Ireland the government wants to work with the EU on how together we can maintain the implementation of the PEACE IV programme. The UK proposes that, without prejudice to the wider discussions on the financial settlement and Structural and Investment Funds, the UK and the EU should agree the continuation of funding for PEACE IV for the duration of the existing programme and, with the Northern Ireland Executive and Irish Government, explore a potential future programme post-2020. The government remains committed to peace and reconciliation programmes and to sustaining cross-border cooperation.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-09-13T13:52:04.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756884/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756884/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756884/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-04","EU Grants and Loans: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions he has had with the EU institutions about funding for Northern Ireland from the EU Peace Programme (a) before and (b) after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756885","Department for International Trade","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Department for International Trade is in the process of developing a cost effective strategy for investigating and tackling dumping, subsidies and safeguards in order to protect domestic industry against injury whilst taking appropriate account of impacts on users and consumers and the wider trade agenda. This work is ongoing and cost estimates cannot yet be finalised.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-09-12T14:23:34.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756885/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756885/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756885/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-04","Overseas Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what estimate he has been made of the cost to the UK of setting up a commercial defence investigatory body to oversee anti-dumping (AD) and anti-subsidy (AS) investigations, follow up complaints by UK industry in line with WTO rules, monitor undertakings and monitor AD and countervailing measures arising out of AS investigations by other countries.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7627"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756886","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-09-11","<p>The European Union (Withdrawal) Bill will convert European Union law into UK law as it applies in the UK at the moment of exit. This will ensure that, wherever possible, the same rules and laws will apply the day after exit as they did before.</p><p>The Government is still making a detailed assessment of what corrections will be required to make that law function appropriately on exit day. The Government’s current estimate is that we will need to make between 800 and 1,000 statutory instruments to make exit a reality in UK law.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-09-11T16:36:43.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756886/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756886/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756886/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-04","Department for Exiting the European Union: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, which EU legislation within his Department's responsibilities will (a) be incorporated into UK law through the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill and (b) require to be amended under powers in that Bill.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7911"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756887","Department for International Trade","false","2017-09-12","<p>The European Union (Withdrawal) Bill will convert European Union law into UK law as it applies in the UK at the moment of exit. This will ensure that, wherever possible, the same rules and laws will apply the day after exit as they did before.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is still making a detailed assessment of what corrections will be required to make that law function appropriately on exit day. The Government’s current estimate is that we will need to make between 800 and 1,000 statutory instruments to make exit a reality in UK law.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-09-12T15:17:13.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756887/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756887/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756887/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-04","Department for International Trade: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, which EU legislation within his Department's responsibilities will (a) be incorporated into UK law through the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill and (b) require to be amended under powers in that Bill.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7916"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756888","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-15","<p>We remain closely engaged with industry to ensure that we are informed of the latest intelligence on the labour market, including on both seasonal and permanent agricultural roles.</p><p> </p><p>As part of this, the government has commissioned the independent Migration Advisory Committee (MAC) to assess the role that EU citizens play in the UK economy and society, and we will work closely with the food and farming industry to consider their specific needs as we develop a new immigration system.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-15T14:36:42.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756888/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756888/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756888/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-04","Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effect on access to non-UK migrant labour in (a) non-seasonal agricultural sectors and (b) the egg industry when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","8399"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756889","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-09-13","<p>Stakeholder engagement is a central element of our plan to build a national consensus around our negotiating position. We are listening and talking to as many pharmaceuticals organisations, companies and institutions as possible.</p><p>The recent Goods position paper outlines our ambitions for a deep and special partnership which allows the freest and most frictionless possible trade in goods. In the context of withdrawal, the paper is clear that we want to reach an agreement that minimises disruption for businesses and consumers, including by agreeing the continued validity of existing market authorisations and compliance activity in regard to the pharmaceuticals sector.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-09-13T13:40:50.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756889/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756889/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756889/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-04","Drugs: Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions he has had with pharmaceutical companies on potential employment in that sector for qualified persons for pharmacovigilance, marketing authorisation holders and qualified people for batch release after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756890","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>​The United Kingdom is a founding member of the World Trade Organization (WTO) and is represented at the WTO by Julian Braithwaite, our Ambassador and Permanent Representative in Geneva. The Government is increasing the size of the WTO team at the UK Mission to the UN in Geneva, including to support this work on the UK’s draft schedules. It will ensure that the Mission has the resources to enable the UK to play a full, active and leading role in the multilateral trading system as we leave the European Union.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-09-12T16:20:08.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756890/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756890/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756890/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-04","World Trade Organisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what estimate has been made of the level of representation the UK will require at the World Trade Organisation and the cost of that representation once the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756891","Department for International Trade","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Department for International Trade is developing a cost effective approach for identifying and tackling trade barriers that discriminate against UK exporters. This work is ongoing and cost estimates cannot yet be finalised.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-09-12T14:29:01.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756891/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756891/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756891/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-04","Overseas Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what estimate he has made of the cost of setting up a department to investigate trade barriers not related to anti-dumping or anti-subsidy investigations in countries that discriminate against UK exports.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7625"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756892","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-12","<p>The European Union (Withdrawal) Bill will convert European Union law into UK law as it applies in the UK at the moment of exit. This will ensure that, wherever possible, the same rules and laws will apply the day after exit as they did before.</p><p>The Government’s current estimate is that we will need to make between 800 and 1,000 statutory instruments to make exit a reality in UK law.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-12T16:35:50.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756892/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756892/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756892/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-04","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, which EU legislation within his Department's responsibilities will (a) be incorporated into UK law through the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill and (b) require to be amended under powers in that Bill.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7903"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756893","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-07","<p>I cannot comment on the specific systems used in Grenfell Tower, as this is a matter for the public inquiry and the on going police investigation.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-07T16:43:15.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756893/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756893/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756893/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Grenfell Tower: Fire Extinguishers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether Grenfell Tower was equipped with a functioning wet or dry riser system.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","8193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756894","Department of Health","false","2017-09-12","<p>There are no circumstances in which sodium chlorite or bleach, sometimes described as Miracle Mineral Solution (MMS), enemas should be used as a treatment to cure autism. We have been clear that MMS, or similar or related compounds, have no proven or conceivable health benefit and can cause serious damage to health, particularly in the case of children.</p><p> </p><p>Where there is any threat to the safety and wellbeing of a child, this may lead to offences of child cruelty being considered, requiring a wider safeguarding response involving the police, children's services and relevant partners. Such a threat could include any harm caused by the administration of a potentially noxious substance. Each case would be judged on its merits.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has received a limited amount of correspondence in relation to the use of bleach enemas as a treatment to cure autism.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","7787","2017-09-12T16:14:32.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756894/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756894/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756894/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-04","Miracle Mineral Solution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what his policy is on the practice of bleach enema as a treatment to cure autism; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","7786"
